[1] UK (Warwick)
Date: Mon 4 Apr 2011
Source: The Redditch Standard [edited]
http://80.194.82.59//obsstandard2/2011/week%2014/redditch/rstr011c080411v1-web.pdf#search=%22measles%22&zoom=100


An outbreak of measles in South Warwickshire has prompted a warning
to parents to ensure their children get the MMR vaccination. 3 cases
of the virus have been discovered, 2 in young people of secondary
school age and one in a young adult. All 3 are receiving care and
advice has been issued to people who they have come into contact
with.

As the virus is highly infectious health bosses are urging parents to
ensure their school age children have received 2 doses of the measles,
mumps, and rubella vaccine (MMR). According to NHS [National Health
Service] Warwickshire take-up of the 1st dose of the vaccine over the
last 5 years has been high at 95 per cent but for the 2nd dose the
level has dropped to 90 per cent. Both doses are needed to ensure
immunity.

Bronwen Spraggett, NHS Warwickshire's immunisation coordinator, said:
"Children are routinely offered the 1st dose of MMR vaccine at
one-year of age and a booster dose at 3 years, 4 months. Routine
catch-up immunisations are offered with the school-leaver booster at
the age of 15.

"Any parent who is concerned that their child has not been fully
vaccinated with MMR vaccine should contact their GP surgery."

Symptoms of measles include fever, cough, spots on the cheek or in
the mouth, and a red blotchy rash. It is spread through coughing and
sneezing and can be very serious in babies, people with lowered immune
systems, such as cancer patients, and unimmunised people.

[Byline: Ian Dipple]

