[6] USA (Florida)
Date: Wed 6 Apr 2011
Source: ClickOrlando.com [edited]
http://www.clickorlando.com/news/27446469/detail.html


State health officials said Tuesday [5 Apr 2011] that 3 travelers
from Minnesota, Michigan, and Texas likely got their cases of the
measles while in the Orlando area. The cases have been confirmed by
laboratory tests, officials said. It's likely that an undiagnosed
infected person visiting or living in Orange County was the source,
officials said.

Health officials advised health care providers to watch out for rash
illnesses until 13 Apr 2011, which is 21 days after the onset of the
latest case. However, they also asked them to remain vigilant after
that.

Tarrant County, Texas, health officials said they were investigating
2 confirmed cases of measles. The 1st case involved a woman in her
30s. The 2nd case, involving a man, was a household contact. They were
the 1st confirmed cases of measles in Tarrant County in 17 years.

Chief epidemiologist Dr Anita Kurian said early indications were that
the 1st confirmed victim was likely exposed during a trip to Orlando
in early March [2011].

The symptoms of measles include fever, runny nose, cough, and a
reddish rash all over the body, health officials said. Measles is
transmitted through the air by breathing, coughing, or sneezing. It is
so contagious that any person who is exposed to it, and is not immune,
will probably get the disease.

Anyone with symptoms of measles should call their doctor as soon as
possible and make special arrangements to prevent contact with others.
Measles is a vaccine-preventable disease. Children should get 2 doses
of the vaccine. Adults who may not have been immunized should contact
their doctor to see if they need the vaccine.

