******
[8] USA (Utah)
Date: Fri 8 Apr 2011
Source: The Salt Lake Tribune [edited]
http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/51592851-78/measles-health-department-cases.html.csp


The Salt Lake Valley Health Department has identified 2 more
individuals who probably have measles. Both individuals had apparently
traveled out of the country, and both are linked to the Olympus High
School teen who has the state's 1st confirmed measles case since 2005,
according to the health department. They are the county's 1st cases
since 1997. "It means that we need to be vigilant," said the health
department's executive director Gary Edwards. "We know that it is now
in the community."

Edwards did not release the ages of the 2 new probable cases. The
health department hasn't yet contacted them, but Edwards doesn't
believe they were hospitalized. Their physician, who reported the
cases to the health department based on news reports of the 1st case,
said they are connected to the teen and had traveled out of the
country. Most measles cases in the US are linked to foreign travel.

Edwards encourages people who believe they or their children have the
measles to call ahead before going to a doctor's office or emergency
room. Facilities need to take precautions so others aren't exposed.
The health department is also urging residents to determine whether
family members are up-to-date on vaccinations.

Also on Friday [8 Apr 2011], 2 students at William Penn Elementary
were sent home from school because they may have been exposed to
measles virus during a visit to Olympus High and have not been
immunized. They will be excluded from school activities through 18 Apr
2011.

[Byline: Heather May]

