[10] Spain (Andalusia)
Date: Tue 5 Apr 2011
Source: ABC de Sevilla [in Spanish, machine trans, edited]
http://www.abcdesevilla.es/20110405/provincia/sevi-sanitario-menos-contagia-tras-201104042202.html


The outbreak of measles [in Andalusia], as reported last Friday [31
Mar 2011] by the Provincial Health Delegation, now involves 432 cases
in Seville, of whom 277 are directly related to the outbreak, not all
of whom are children. It was confirmed yesterday [4 Apr 2011] that a
doctor at Valmey Hospital had contracted measles as a direct
consequence of this outbreak.

The outbreak is affecting several provinces of Andalusia and, in the
case of Seville, the Ministry of Health has recommended that all
parents with children between 6 and 15 months in Seville, Alcala de
Guadaira, Dos Hermanas, and Mairena del Aljarafe, and Tomares should
attend a health centre to receive measles vaccination as "an
exceptional and temporary measure for the duration of the current
situation."

The Andalusian Autonomous Government pointed out, moreover, that
those under the age of 12 months who had already been vaccinated
should receive a booster dose at 15 months and 3 years, whereas
infants between 12 and 15 months who had been vaccinated already, need
only be revaccinated at 3 years.

The Health Department also requested that parents check their
children's vaccination records to ensure that they had received 2
doses of MMR vaccine at 15 months and 3 years as required by the
childhood vaccination schedule.

The Andalusian government stressed last week [week of 28 Mar 2011]
that "the only way to prevent this disease is through vaccination."
Measles presents as a rash of red sots and may include, among its
symptoms, otitis media, croup, pneumonia, diarrhea, seizure, or
febrile convulsions.

Children under 6 months are immunized naturally (both from their
mother during pregnancy and subsequently through breastfeeding), thus
that "it is not necessary vaccinate at this age."

The increased mobility of people and consequent disruption of
vaccination campaigns for diseases such as measles, which was
considered eradicated decades ago, are identified as one cause of the
outbreak of the disease in Andalusia.

The present outbreak had its 1st episode late last year [2010] in
Granada, a province where more than 50 cases were recorded in a school
where parents had declined to have their children vaccinated until
required to ultimately by a judicial decree.

--
