[11] Spain (Canary Islands)
Date: Fri 8 Apr 2011
Source: Canarias al Dia [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://www.canariasaldia.com/noticia.php?noticia_id=264033


Canariasaldia.com has been told that the University Hospital Nuestra
Senora de La Candelaria (Hunsc) [in Santa Cruz de Tenerife] has begun
vaccinating their staff following an outbreak of measles virus
infection in the hospital. The 1s case, a nurse in the recovery ward,
was recorded 15 days ago. Shortly afterwards an anesthesiologist and
several nurses in the Emergency Unit fell with similar symptoms.
Doctors believe that the emergence of this disease, which was believed
to have been nearly eradicated in Western Europe, is a consequence of
deficiencies in vaccine coverage.

For the present health authorities are providing measles vaccination
for people aged between 25 and 35 years, the age group most at risk of
infection. The outbreak in the Canary Islands, for the moment limited
to a very concrete zone, joins those reported in Seville (where there
have been more than 400 cases) and in Granada.

Vaccination is being implemented by Hunsc healthcare providers with
commendable urgency and medical workers are being trained to identify
case of measles and apply appropriate treatment.

Measles begins with viral conjunctivitis and continues with a rash,
sore throat, and high fever. In addition, the patient usually has
small white spots on the palate, which are known as "Koplik spots". In
severe cases, onset of pneumonia is possible, causing a serious health
risk to the patient. Rarely encephalitis can occur.

The disease is highly contagious and is spread through direct contact
with the patient or when saliva droplets expelled to the outside after
sneezing or coughing.

[Byline: Hector Fajardo]

