[13] Philippines
Date Tue 5 Apr 2011
Source: ABS-CBN News [edited]
http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/lifestyle/04/05/11/over-2000-measles-cases-jan-march


In just the 1st 3 months of the year (January-19 Mar 2011), over 2000
cases of measles have already been recorded in the country. 5 of these
resulted in death.

The majority of the cases are in the National Capital Region [NCR]
(311 cases). The rest are in Central Luzon (298), Bicol region (277),
Calabarzon (238), Davao region (197), Ilocos region (174), and
Zamboanga peninsula (163). In NCR, most of the cases are in Manila
(101). Quezon City, meanwhile, had 50 cases, while Caloocan had 36.

To address this problem, the Department of Health (DOH) launched
yesterday [4 Apr 2011] a month-long nationwide campaign "Iligtas sa
Tigdas ang Pinas", a [measles-rubella] vaccination campaign targeting
children aged 9 months up to 8 years old. The campaign hopes to curb
the rising incidence of measles cases, which reached 6000 in 2010.
Vaccination teams dubbed "bakunadoors" will go door-to-door to
administer free vaccinations.

The DOH asked parents to allow vaccination teams into their homes to
conduct the activity. Measles is a serious illness, according to the
DOH. If left untreated, it can lead to complications such as
bronchopneumonia and diarrhea, and even death.

[Byline: Sol Aragones]

